The default pattern here should be: plain exported domain functions, with classes used only in the narrow cases where the module is already behaving like a cohesive policy object.

That recommendation matches your existing code more closely than a blanket “service class” rule:

- Your own guidance explicitly says to extract god handlers into domain-layer functions and to follow the host module’s existing export style, not introduce classes arbitrarily: [god-handler-extraction-requires-domain-function-pattern.md](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/docs/solutions/logic-errors/god-handler-extraction-requires-domain-function-pattern.md:1).
- The biggest successful extraction example is function-oriented: [session.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/feeds/session.ts:1) owns `resolveSessionCity`, `resolveDistanceFilter`, `fetchCityContext`, `createSession`, `buildSnapshot`, and the route became an orchestrator: [books/discover/session/route.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/books/discover/session/route.ts:1).
- Your class-based modules are the exception, and they have a specific shape: singleton policy modules with private helpers and stable invariants, e.g. [BookMutationService.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/domain/BookMutationService.ts:1), [UserBanService.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/domain/UserBanService.ts:1), [UserActivityService.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/backend/domain/UserActivityService.ts:1).

The practical pattern I’d use is three layers, not one:

1. `route.ts`
   Keep this as export/wiring only with `createRouteHandler` and middleware composition. You already do this well in places like [user/[userId]/book/status/route.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/book/status/route.ts:1).

2. request handler file
   Own only HTTP concerns: auth, params/body parsing, calling one use-case/domain function, mapping domain errors to `responseHelpers`. This is where [updateBookStatus.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/book/status/updateBookStatus.ts:1) and [postConfirmSwap.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/user/[userId]/swaps/confirm/handlers/postConfirmSwap.ts:1) are still carrying too much domain logic.

3. backend/domain or feature module
   Put the business flow here as plain exported functions by default. Example shape:
   - `confirmSwap(params)`
   - `invalidateCompetingSwaps(params)`
   - `reportAndCancelSwaps(params)` like [reportService.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/apps/tma/src/app/api/users/report/services/reportService.ts:1)

My recommendation on the class vs function question:

- Use plain functions by default when the extracted logic is a use case or workflow.
- Use a class only when the module has one cohesive responsibility, several private helper methods, and a stable singleton identity that callers reuse.
- Do not create “service classes” just to group stateless functions. In this codebase that adds ceremony without buying DI, polymorphism, or better testing.

A simple decision rule:

- If the code reads like “do this workflow for this request” and returns a result, make it a function.
- If the code reads like “this module owns mutation policy/invariants for this aggregate” and benefits from private helpers, a class is reasonable.
- If the route is over 150-200 lines because of branching, queries, transactions, and side effects, extract the workflow first as a function. Only promote to a class if repeated use reveals a real object boundary.

For this repo specifically, I would standardize on “functional application services”:

```ts
// handler
export async function postConfirmSwapHandler(...) {
  const user = authContext.user;
  const parsed = await validateConfirmRequest(request);
  if (parsed.response) return parsed.response;

  try {
    const result = await confirmSwap({
      actorUserId: user.id,
      swapId: parsed.body.swapId,
      bookId: parsed.body.bookId,
    });

    return createSuccessResponse(request, result.responseBody);
  } catch (error) {
    // map domain errors -> responseHelpers here
  }
}
```

```ts
// backend use-case/domain module
export async function confirmSwap(input: ConfirmSwapInput): Promise<ConfirmSwapResult> {
  // load + authorize + validate state
  // transaction for main mutation
  // invalidate competing swaps
  // queue notifications
  // invalidate caches
  // return domain result DTO
}
```

That gives you the right separation for your current architecture:

- `createRouteHandler` is not a full application-service abstraction; it mainly does method dispatch/logging: [routeHandler.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/api/routeHandler.ts:1).
- Auth/error helpers already assume handlers remain thin orchestrators: [responseHelpers.ts](/Users/rsboarder/workspace/bookmatcher/packages/core/src/lib/api/responseHelpers.ts:1).
- The repo already has a proven mix: function-oriented workflows, class-oriented invariant/policy modules.

If you want a hard team rule, I’d make it this:

- New route extractions default to plain exported functions in the owning backend module.
- New classes require justification: shared invariant owner, meaningful private helper cohesion, or a singleton policy object.
- Routes should only do auth, request parsing, use-case invocation, analytics, and response formatting.

That is the most consistent pattern with the code you already have, and it avoids drifting into class-heavy architecture without a real payoff.

